                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Tatas to forge closer ties with Fiat
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                          Forster: Mulling growth plans                                  
	Mumbai, Aug. 12: Tata Motors plans to introduce more cars from the Fiat stable through their 50:50 joint venture company Fiat India Automobiles Ltd.        
	We plan to expand the Fiat range, Carl Peter Forster, chief executive and managing director of the Tata Motors group, told reporters here today. We will also increase sales and marketing support to the brand. Forster has been at the helm of the auto maker for six months.        
	Tata Motors also has a marketing and distribution tie-up with Fiat. The joint venture between the two automobile companies makes the Grande Punto, Linea and the Palio Stile models.         
	The duo are likely to explore opportunities in a Tata stronghold  commercial vehicles.         
	Forster said Tata Motors saw great potential for the commercial vehicles  especially trucks  business globally and it could explore synergies in that space with Fiat in various geographies.         
	The company plans to set up another plant to make small trucks in India and launch more models by the year-end.        
	Forster, who earlier led General Motors in Europe, said the company would take a fresh look at the conventional wisdom of sourcing engines from outside.         
	At present, the companys British brands Jaguar and Land Rover are facing a shortage of engines that they source from Ford Motor Company.         
	We have to challenge this practice in our minds and look at various other possibilities, he added.        
	Tata Motors has recorded an impressive first-quarter performance aided by a turnaround at Jaguar Land Rover.         
	Net profit for the three months ended June 30, 2010 stood at Rs 1,988 crore compared with a loss in the corresponding quarter a year ago.        
	Jaguar and Land Rover posted a profit of 221 million during the first quarter of this fiscal.         
	Forster said Jaguar Land Rovers improved performance was a result of re-working the product portfolio, improvement in sales and marketing activities and an overhaul of the companys processes.                                                                                                                                      
